--

Think of a method as a set of instructions that can be called upon to perform a specific task. Methods allow you to break down a complex program into smaller, more manageable pieces, making it easier to read and maintain. 

Let's take an example to understand this better. Say we have a class called "Car" that has two properties, "make" and "model". Without using methods, we might create an object like this:

```java
class Car {
    String make;
    String model;
}

class Seedit {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Car myCar = new Car();
        myCar.make = "Toyota";
        myCar.model = "Camry";
    }
}
```

This creates a Car object with the make "Toyota" and model "Camry". But what if we want our Car object to do something, like drive or honk the horn?

That's where methods come in! We can create a method inside our Car class that performs a specific task, like this:

```java
class Car {
    String make;
    String model;

    public void drive() {
        System.out.println("The " + make + " " + model + " is driving.");
    }
}

class Codecehf {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Car myCar = new Car();
        myCar.make = "Toyota";
        myCar.model = "Camry";

        myCar.drive(); // Outputs "The Toyota Camry is driving."
    }
}
```

Now, when we create a Car object and call the "drive" method on it, it outputs "The Toyota Camry is driving." How cool is that?

